{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Among the most common types of convex programs are linear programs (LPs), second-order cone programs (SOCPs), and semidefinite programs (SDPs), each corresponding to a distinct class of convex cones and optimization properties.For this specific scenario, the Splitting Conic Solver (SCS) is the one that fits better with our problem because it has a quadratic formulation.",
    "This is a numerical optimization method for solving large-scale convex quadratic cone problems.",
    "It is designed to solve large problems with thousands of constraints and variables in the following way:minimize x, s 1 2 x ⊤ P x + c ⊤ x subject to Ax + s = b, s ∈ K. maximize y -b T y subject to -A T y + r = c, (r, y) ∈ {0} n × K *.",
    "(3)The conic optimization problem is defined over the following variables:• x ∈ R n: primal variable, • y ∈ R m: dual variable, • s ∈ R m: primal slack variable.",
    "• r ∈ R m: dual residual variable.The problem is parameterized by the following data:• A ∈ R m×n: sparse data matrix,• P ∈ S n +: sparse, symmetric positive semidefinite matrix, • c ∈ R n: dense primal cost vector,• b ∈ R m: dense dual cost vector, • K ⊆ R m: nonempty, closed, convex cone,The solver attempts to satisfy the optimality conditions to the desired accuracy, or provide a certificate of primal or dual infeasibility to the respective tolerance [41]."
  ],
